# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dalle-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The first version of DALL-E was announced in January 2021.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In the following year, its successor DALL-E 2 was released.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 3 was released natively into ChatGPT for ChatGPT Plus and ChatGPT Enterprise customers in October 2023, with availability via OpenAI's API and "Labs" platform provided in early November.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Microsoft implemented the model in Bing's Image Creator tool and plans to implement it into their Designer app.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] With Bing's Image Creator tool, Microsoft Copilot runs on DALL-E 3.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In March 2025, DALL-E 3 was replaced in ChatGPT by GPT Image's native image-generation capabilities.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E was revealed by OpenAI in a blog post on 5 January 2021, and uses a version of GPT-3 modified to generate images.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] On 6 April 2022, OpenAI announced DALL-E 2, a successor designed to generate more realistic images at higher resolutions that "can combine concepts, attributes, and styles".
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] On 20 July 2022, DALL-E 2 entered into a beta phase with invitations sent to 1 million waitlisted individuals; users could generate a certain number of images for free every month and may purchase more.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Access had previously been restricted to pre-selected users for a research preview due to concerns about ethics and safety.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] On 28 September 2022, DALL-E 2 was opened to everyone and the waitlist requirement was removed.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In September 2023, OpenAI announced their latest image model, DALL-E 3, capable of understanding "significantly more nuance and detail" than previous iterations.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In early November 2022, OpenAI released DALL-E 2 as an API, allowing developers to integrate the model into their own applications.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Microsoft unveiled their implementation of DALL-E 2 in their Designer app and Image Creator tool included in Bing and Microsoft Edge.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The API operates on a cost-per-image basis, with prices varying depending on image resolution.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Volume discounts are available to companies working with OpenAI's enterprise team.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The software's name is a portmanteau of the names of animated robot Pixar character WALL-E and the Spanish surrealist artist Salvador Dalí.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In February 2024, OpenAI began adding watermarks to DALL-E generated images, containing metadata in the C2PA (Coalition for Content Provenance and Authenticity) standard promoted by the Content Authenticity Initiative.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The first generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) model was initially developed by OpenAI in 2018, using a Transformer architecture.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The first iteration, GPT-1, was scaled up to produce GPT-2 in 2019; in 2020, it was scaled up again to produce GPT-3, with 175 billion parameters.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E has three components: a discrete VAE, an autoregressive decoder-only Transformer model (12 billion parameters) similar to GPT-3, and a CLIP pair of image encoder and text encoder.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The discrete VAE can convert an image to a sequence of tokens, and conversely, convert a sequence of tokens back to an image.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] This is necessary as the Transformer model does not directly process image data.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The input to the Transformer model is a sequence of tokenised image caption followed by tokenised image patches.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The image caption is in English, tokenised by byte pair encoding (vocabulary size 16384), and can be up to 256 tokens long.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Each image is a 256×256 RGB image, divided into 32×32 patches of 4×4 each.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Each patch is then converted by a discrete variational autoencoder to a token (vocabulary size 8192).
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E was developed and announced to the public in conjunction with CLIP (Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training).
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] CLIP is a separate model based on contrastive learning that was trained on 400 million pairs of images with text captions scraped from the Internet.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Its role is to "understand and rank" DALL-E's output by predicting which caption from a list of 32,768 captions randomly selected from the dataset (of which one was the correct answer) is most appropriate for an image.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] A trained CLIP pair is used to filter a larger initial list of images generated by DALL-E to select the image that is closest to the text prompt.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 2 uses 3.5 billion parameters, a smaller number than its predecessor.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Instead of an autoregressive Transformer, DALL-E 2 uses a diffusion model conditioned on CLIP image embeddings, which, during inference, are generated from CLIP text embeddings by a prior model.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] This is the same architecture as that of Stable Diffusion, released a few months later.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] While a technical report was written for DALL-E 3, it does not include training or implementation details of the model, instead focusing on the improved prompt following capabilities developed for DALL-E 3.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E can generate imagery in multiple styles, including photorealistic imagery, paintings, and emoji.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] It can "manipulate and rearrange" objects in its images, and can correctly place design elements in novel compositions without explicit instruction.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Furthermore, DALL-E exhibits a broad understanding of visual and design trends.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E can produce images for a wide variety of arbitrary descriptions from various viewpoints with only rare failures.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Mark Riedl, an associate professor at the Georgia Tech School of Interactive Computing, found that DALL-E could blend concepts (described as a key element of human creativity).
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Its visual reasoning ability is sufficient to solve Raven's Matrices (visual tests often administered to humans to measure intelligence).
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 3 follows complex prompts with more accuracy and detail than its predecessors, and is able to generate more coherent and accurate text.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 3 is integrated into ChatGPT Plus.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Given an existing image, DALL-E 2 and DALL-E 3 can produce "variations" of the image as individual outputs based on the original, as well as edit the image to modify or expand upon it.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The "inpainting" and "outpainting" abilities of these models use context from an image to fill in missing areas using a medium consistent with the original, following a given prompt.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] For example, this can be used to insert a new subject into an image, or expand an image beyond its original borders.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 2's language understanding has limits.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] It is sometimes unable to distinguish "A yellow book and a red vase" from "A red book and a yellow vase" or "A panda making latte art" from "Latte art of a panda".
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] It generates images of an astronaut riding a horse when presented with the prompt "a horse riding an astronaut".
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] It also fails to generate the correct images in a variety of circumstances.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Requesting more than three objects, negation, numbers, and connected sentences may result in mistakes, and object features may appear on the wrong object.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Additional limitations include generating text, ambigrams and other forms of typography, which often results in dream-like gibberish.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The model also has a limited capacity to address scientific information, such as astronomy or medical imagery.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 2's reliance on public datasets influences its results and leads to algorithmic bias in some cases, such as generating higher numbers of men than women for requests that do not mention gender.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 2's training data was filtered to remove violent and sexual imagery, but this was found to increase bias in some cases such as reducing the frequency of women being generated.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] OpenAI hypothesise that this may be because women were more likely to be sexualised in training data which caused the filter to influence results.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In September 2022, OpenAI confirmed to *The Verge* that DALL-E invisibly inserts phrases into user prompts to address bias in results; for instance, "black man" and "Asian woman" are inserted into prompts that do not specify gender or race.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] OpenAI claims to address concerns for potential "racy content" – containing nudity or sexual content generation, with DALL-E 3 through input/output filters, blocklists, ChatGPT refusals, and model level interventions.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] However, DALL-E 3 continues to disproportionally represent people as White, female, and youthful.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Users are able to somewhat remedy this through more specific prompts for image generation.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] A concern about DALL-E 2 and similar image generation models is that they could be used to propagate deepfakes and other forms of misinformation.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] As an attempt to mitigate this, the software rejects prompts involving public figures and uploads containing human faces.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Prompts containing potentially objectionable content are blocked, and uploaded images are analysed to detect offensive material.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] A disadvantage of prompt-based filtering is that it is easy to bypass using alternative phrases that result in a similar output.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] For example, the word "blood" is filtered, but "ketchup" and "red liquid" are not.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Another concern about DALL-E 2 and similar models is that they could cause technological unemployment for artists, photographers, and graphic designers due to their accuracy and popularity.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E 3 is designed to block users from generating art in the style of currently-living artists.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] While OpenAI states that images produced using these models do not require permission to reprint, sell, or merchandise, legal concerns have been raised regarding who owns those images.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In 2023 Microsoft pitched the United States Department of Defense to use DALL-E models to train battlefield management systems.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] In January 2024 OpenAI removed its blanket ban on military and warfare use from its usage policies.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Most coverage of DALL-E focuses on a small subset of "surreal" or "quirky" outputs.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] DALL-E's output for "an illustration of a baby daikon radish in a tutu walking a dog" was mentioned in pieces from *Input*, NBC, *Nature*, and other publications.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Its output for "an armchair in the shape of an avocado" was also widely covered.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] According to *MIT Technology Review*, one of OpenAI's objectives was to "give language models a better grasp of the everyday concepts that humans use to make sense of things".
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Wall Street investors have had a positive reception of DALL-E 2, with some firms thinking it could represent a turning point for a future multi-trillion dollar industry.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] By mid-2019, OpenAI had already received over $1 billion in funding from Microsoft and Khosla Ventures, and in January 2023, following the launch of DALL-E 2 and ChatGPT, received an additional $10 billion in funding from Microsoft.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Japan's anime community has had a negative reaction to DALL-E 2 and similar models.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Two arguments are typically presented by artists against the software.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] The first is that AI art is not art because it is not created by a human with intent.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] "The juxtaposition of AI-generated images with their own work is degrading and undermines the time and skill that goes into their art.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] AI-driven image generation tools have been heavily criticized by artists because they are trained on human-made art scraped from the web." The second is the trouble with copyright law and data text-to-image models are trained on.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] OpenAI has not released information about what dataset(s) were used to train DALL-E 2, inciting concern from some that the work of artists has been used for training without permission.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Copyright laws surrounding these topics are inconclusive at the moment.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] After integrating DALL-E 3 into Bing Chat and ChatGPT, Microsoft and OpenAI faced criticism for excessive content filtering, with critics saying DALL-E had been "lobotomized." The flagging of images generated by prompts such as "man breaks server rack with sledgehammer" was cited as evidence.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Over the first days of its launch, filtering was reportedly increased to the point where images generated by some of Bing's own suggested prompts were being blocked.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] *TechRadar* argued that leaning too heavily on the side of caution could limit DALL-E's value as a creative tool.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Since OpenAI has not released source code or weights for any of the three models, there have been several attempts to create open-source models offering similar capabilities.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Released in 2022 on Hugging Face's Spaces platform, Craiyon (formerly DALL-E Mini until a name change was requested by OpenAI in June 2022) is an AI model based on the original DALL-E that was trained on unfiltered data from the Internet.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] It attracted substantial media attention in mid-2022, after its release due to its capacity for producing humorous imagery.
[src:dalle-model/dall-e] Another example of an open source text-to-image model is Stable Diffusion by Stability AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been used for cybercrime, and to deceive and manipulate people through fake news and deepfakes.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models have been trained on copyrighted works without the rightholders' permission.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI systems use large-scale data centers, whose environmental impacts include electronic waste, consumption of fresh water for cooling, and high energy consumption that is estimated to be growing steadily.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The origins of algorithmically generated media can be traced to the development of the Markov chain, which has been used to model natural language since the early 20th century.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Russian mathematician Andrey Markov introduced the concept in 1906, including an analysis of vowel and consonant patterns in *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Once trained on a text corpus, a Markov chain can generate probabilistic text.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] By the early 1970s, artists began using computers to extend generative techniques beyond Markov models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Harold Cohen developed and exhibited works produced by AARON, a pioneering computer program designed to autonomously create paintings.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The terms generative AI planning or generative planning were used in the 1980s and 1990s to refer to AI planning systems, especially computer-aided process planning, used to generate sequences of actions to reach a specified goal.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI planning systems used symbolic AI methods such as state space search and constraint satisfaction and were a "relatively mature" technology by the early 1990s.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] They were used to generate crisis action plans for military use, process plans for manufacturing and decision plans such as in prototype autonomous spacecraft.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Machine learning uses both discriminative models and generative models to predict or generate data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Beginning in the late 2000s and early 2010s, advances in deep learning led to major improvements in image classification, speech recognition, and natural language processing.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Neural networks in this period were typically trained as discriminative models due to the relative difficulty of training generative models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2014, the introduction of models such as the variational autoencoder (VAE) and generative adversarial network (GAN) enabled effective deep generative modeling of complex data such as images.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2017, the Transformer architecture enabled further advances in generative modeling compared to earlier long short-term memory (LSTM) networks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This led to the development of generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) models, beginning with GPT-1 in 2018.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2020, the release of 15.ai, a free web application created by an anonymous MIT researcher that could generate convincing character voices using minimal training data, was one of the earliest publicly available uses for generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The platform is credited as the first mainstream service for audio deepfakes.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2021, DALL-E, a closed-source transformer-based generative model developed by OpenAI, drew widespread attention to text-to-image generation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other projects, including open-source approaches such as VQGAN+CLIP and DALL·E Mini (later renamed Craiyon), made similar systems more accessible to the public.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Dream by Wombo was released at the end of 2021, followed by the releases of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion in 2022.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In November 2022, ChatGPT was released to the public.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, it popularized generative AI for general-purpose text-based tasks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a 2024 survey by marketing research firm Ipsos, Asia–Pacific countries were significantly more optimistic than Western societies about generative AI and show higher adoption rates.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite expressing concerns about privacy and the pace of change, 68% of Asia-Pacific respondents believed that AI was having a positive impact on the world, compared to 57% globally.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a survey by SAS and Coleman Parkes Research, as of 2023, 83% of Chinese respondents were using the technology, exceeding both the global average of 54% and the U.S. rate of 65%.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A UN report indicated that Chinese entities filed over 38,000 generative AI patents from 2014 to 2023, more than any other country.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 survey by the Just So Soul social media app reported that 18% of respondents born after 2000 used generative AI "almost every day", and that over 60% of respondents like or love AI-generated content (AIGC), while less than 3% dislike or hate it.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative artificial intelligence has been applied across multiple industries for content creation and automation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In healthcare, generative models are used for drug discovery and the generation of synthetic medical data to train diagnostic systems.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In finance, they are used for report drafting, data generation, and customer service automation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Media and entertainment industries use generative systems for tasks such as music composition, script development, and image or video generation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Researchers and policymakers have raised concerns regarding accuracy, misuse, and impacts on academic and professional work.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Large language models (LLMs) are trained on tokenized text from large corpora and are capable of natural language processing, machine translation, and natural language generation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] LLMs can be used as foundation models for a variety of downstream tasks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] They can also be trained on source code to generate programs from prompts.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2016, DeepMind's WaveNet demonstrated that deep neural networks can generate raw audio waveforms.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This enabled more realistic speech synthesis compared to earlier approaches.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Subsequent systems such as Tacotron 2 demonstrated end-to-end neural text-to-speech generation.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to create visual art.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Such systems are trained on image–text pairs.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Examples include Stable Diffusion, DALL-E, and Midjourney.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to produce photorealistic videos.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Systems such as Runway have demonstrated text-to-video generation capabilities.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can be used for motion planning and robot control by learning from prior data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can assist in automating 3D modeling tasks, including generating 3D assets from text or images.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] World models are neural networks designed to learn representations of physical environments, including spatial and dynamic properties.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Recent multimodal systems have expanded these capabilities by integrating vision, language, and action into unified models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems have been used in mathematics and computer science to generate candidate computer programs, proofs, constructions, or algorithms.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced FunSearch, a method for creating computer programs that solve mathematical and algorithmic problems.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] FunSearch was used to discover new mathematical constructions in the cap set problem and the bin packing problem.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, which was used to discover small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and have been integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an AI system for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] AlphaEvolve uses LLMs to propose code changes, automated evaluators to assess each candidate, and an evolutionary process to iteratively improve algorithms.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced GNoME, a method to propose candidate inorganic crystal structures for computational screening and experimental synthesis in material science.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other material science methods include MatterGen, CDVAE, and CrystalFlow.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative engine optimization (GEO) is the practice of structuring digital content and managing online presence to improve visibility in responses generated by generative AI systems.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The practice influences the way large language models (LLMs) retrieve, summarize, and present information in response to user queries.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Related terms include answer engine optimization (AEO) and artificial intelligence optimization (AIO).
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models are used to power chatbot products such as ChatGPT, programming tools such as GitHub Copilot, text-to-image products such as Midjourney, and text-to-video products such as Runway Gen-2.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI features have been integrated into a variety of existing commercially available products such as Microsoft Office (Microsoft Copilot), Google Photos, and the Adobe Suite (Adobe Firefly).
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI models are also available as open-source software, including Stable Diffusion and the LLaMA language model.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller generative AI models with up to a few billion parameters can run on smartphones, embedded devices, and personal computers.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, LLaMA-7B (a version with 7 billion parameters) can run on a Raspberry Pi 4 and one version of Stable Diffusion can run on an iPhone 11.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Larger models with tens of billions of parameters can run on laptop or desktop computers.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] To achieve an acceptable speed, models of this size may require accelerators such as the GPU chips produced by NVIDIA and AMD or the Neural Engine included in Apple silicon products.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, the 65 billion parameter version of LLaMA can be configured to run on a desktop PC.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The advantages of running generative AI locally include protection of privacy and intellectual property, and avoidance of rate limiting and censorship.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The subreddit r/LocalLLaMA in particular focuses on using consumer-grade gaming graphics cards through such techniques as compression.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Language models with hundreds of billions of parameters, such as GPT-4 or PaLM, typically run on datacenter computers equipped with arrays of GPUs (such as NVIDIA's H100) or AI accelerator chips (such as Google's TPU).
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] These very large models are typically accessed as cloud services over the Internet.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2022, the United States New Export Controls on Advanced Computing and Semiconductors to China imposed restrictions on exports to China of GPU and AI accelerator chips used for generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Chips such as the NVIDIA A800 and the Biren Technology BR104 were developed to meet the requirements of the sanctions.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is free software on the market capable of recognizing text generated by generative artificial intelligence (such as GPTZero), as well as images, audio or video coming from it.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Potential mitigation strategies for detecting generative AI content include digital watermarking, content authentication, information retrieval, and machine learning classifier models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite claims of accuracy, both free and paid AI text detectors have frequently produced false positives, mistakenly accusing students of submitting AI-generated work.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are a generative modeling technique which consist of two neural networks—the generator and the discriminator—trained simultaneously in a competitive setting.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The generator creates synthetic data by transforming random noise into samples that resemble the training dataset.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The discriminator is trained to distinguish the authentic data from synthetic data produced by the generator.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The two models engage in a minimax game: the generator aims to create increasingly realistic data to "fool" the discriminator, while the discriminator improves its ability to distinguish real from fake data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This continuous training setup enables the generator to produce high-quality and realistic outputs.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Variational autoencoders (VAEs) are deep learning models that probabilistically encode data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] They are typically used for tasks such as noise reduction from images, data compression, identifying unusual patterns, and facial recognition.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike standard autoencoders, which compress input data into a fixed latent representation, VAEs model the latent space as a probability distribution, allowing for smooth sampling and interpolation between data points.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The encoder ("recognition model") maps input data to a latent space, producing means and variances that define a probability distribution.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The decoder ("generative model") samples from this latent distribution and attempts to reconstruct the original input.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Transformers became the foundation for the generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) series developed by OpenAI, replacing traditional recurrent and convolutional models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The self-attention mechanism enables the model to determine the relative importance of each token in a sequence when predicting the next token, thereby improving contextual understanding.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike recurrent neural networks, transformers process tokens in parallel, which improves training efficiency and scalability.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, a group of companies including OpenAI, Alphabet, and Meta signed a voluntary agreement with the Biden administration in July 2023 to watermark AI-generated content.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In October 2023, Executive Order 14110 applied the Defense Production Act to require all US companies to report information to the federal government when training certain high-impact AI models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the European Union (EU), the Artificial Intelligence Act includes requirements to disclose copyrighted material used to train generative AI systems, and to label any AI-generated output as such.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In China, the Interim Measures for the Management of Generative AI Services introduced by the Cyberspace Administration of China regulates any public-facing generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] It includes requirements to watermark generated images or videos, regulations on training data and label quality, restrictions on personal data collection, and a guideline that generative AI services must "adhere to socialist core values".
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems such as ChatGPT and Midjourney are trained on large, publicly available datasets that include copyrighted works.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI developers have argued that such training is protected under fair use, while copyright holders have argued that it infringes their rights.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Proponents of fair use training have argued that it is a transformative use and does not involve making copies of copyrighted works available to the public.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Critics have argued that image generators such as Midjourney can create nearly-identical copies of some copyrighted images, and that generative AI programs compete with the content they are trained on.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] As of 2024, several lawsuits related to the use of copyrighted material in training are ongoing.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Getty Images has sued Stability AI over the use of its images to train Stable Diffusion.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Both the Authors Guild and The New York Times have sued Microsoft and OpenAI over the use of their works to train ChatGPT.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A separate question is whether AI-generated works can qualify for copyright protection.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The United States Copyright Office has ruled that works created by artificial intelligence without any human input cannot be copyrighted, because they lack human authorship.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Some legal professionals have suggested that *Naruto v.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals held that non-humans cannot be copyright holders of artistic works, could be a potential precedent in copyright litigation over works created by generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the office has also begun taking public input to determine if these rules need to be refined for generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Whether such modifications rise to the minimum standard of originality required under Feist will depend on a case-by-case determination.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In those cases where they do, the output should be copyrightable" Subsequently, the USCO registered the first visual artwork to be composed of entirely AI-generated materials, titled "A Single Piece of American Cheese".
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The development of generative AI has raised concerns from governments, businesses, and individuals, resulting in protests, legal actions, calls to pause AI experiments, and actions by multiple governments.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In addition, generative AI has a significant carbon footprint.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study presented in the 2026 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems found that overreliance on generative AI can decrease one's ability to discern misinformation, the study tracked participants, mostly from the UK and US, for a period of 4 weeks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to generate and modify academic prose, paraphrase sources, and translate languages.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The use of generative AI in a classroom setting has challenged traditional definitions of academic plagiarism, leading to a "cat-and-mouse" dynamic between students using AI and institutions attempting to detect it.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the immediate wake of ChatGPT's release, many school districts and universities issued temporary bans on the technology, though many institutions have since moved toward policies of managed integration.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the implementation of these policies often lacks clarity.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Research suggests that the burden of interpreting "acceptable use" frequently falls on individual students and teachers, creating an environment where academic honesty becomes difficult to define and enforce.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A commonly proposed use for teachers is grading and giving feedback.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies like Pearson and ETS use AI to score grammar, mechanics, usage, and style, but not for main ideas or overall structure.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The National Council of Teachers of English stated that machine scoring makes students feel their writing is not worth reading.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI scoring has also given unfair results for students from different ethnic backgrounds.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, it was reported that image generation AI has resulted in 70% of the jobs for video game illustrators in China being lost.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In July 2023, developments in generative AI contributed to the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Fran Drescher, president of the Screen Actors Guild, declared that "artificial intelligence poses an existential threat to creative professions" during the 2023 SAG-AFTRA strike.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Voice generation AI has been seen as a potential challenge to the voice acting sector.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, a 2025 study concluded that the US labor market had so far not experienced a discernible disruption from generative AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Another study reported that Danish workers who used chatbots saved 2.8% of their time on average, and found no significant change in earnings or hours worked.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, *Futurism* broke the story that CNET had been using an undisclosed internal AI tool to write at least 77 of its stories; after the news broke, CNET posted corrections to 41 of the stories.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, *Die Aktuelle* published an AI-generated fake interview of Michael Schumacher.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2024, *Futurism* noted that a content management system video by AdVon Commerce, which had used generative AI to produce articles for many of the aforementioned outlets, appeared to show that they "had produced tens of thousands of articles for more than 150 publishers".
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, a report from the American Sunlight Project stated that Pravda network was publishing as many as 10,000 articles a day, and concluded that much of this content aimed to push Russian narratives into large language models through their training data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2024, Reuters Institute published its *Digital News Report for 2024*.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a survey of people in America and Europe, Reuters Institute reports that 52% and 47% respectively are uncomfortable with news produced by "mostly AI with some human oversight", and 23% and 15% respectively report being comfortable.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] 42% of Americans and 33% of Europeans reported that they were comfortable with news produced by "mainly human with some help from AI".
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The results of global surveys reported that people were more uncomfortable with news topics including politics (46%), crime (43%), and local news (37%) produced by AI than other news topics.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2025 Pew Research Survey found roughly half of all U.S. adults say that AI will have a very (24%) or somewhat (26%) negative impact on the news people get in the U.S. over the next 20 years.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A language model may associate certain professions with specific genders if such patterns are prevalent in the data.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similarly, image generation systems prompted with terms such as "a photo of a CEO" have been observed to disproportionately generate images of white male individuals when trained on biased datasets.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI software, when using voice recognition software in particular, struggles to recognize and understand speech impediments.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, people with a stutter struggle to activate voice-activated assistants such as Gemini and Siri due to how the software was trained.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies that use AI systems to hire for new positions also filter out people with accents and speech due to voice recognition software incorrectly transcribing how candidates speak during the interview process.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Because of this, people with disabilities and uncommon accents don't often make it to a human interviewer when these generative AI systems are used.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This is due to many AI models being trained and produced in the United States, and therefore, off of American accents.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes (a portmanteau of "deep learning" and "fake") are AI-generated media that take a person in an existing image or video and replace them with someone else's likeness using artificial neural networks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes have garnered widespread attention and concerns for their uses in deepfake celebrity pornographic videos, revenge porn, fake news, hoaxes, health disinformation, financial fraud, and covert foreign election interference.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Instances of users abusing software to generate controversial statements in the vocal style of celebrities, public officials, and other famous individuals have raised ethical concerns over voice generation AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In response, companies such as ElevenLabs have stated that they would work on mitigating potential abuse through safeguards and identity verification.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Concerns and fandoms have spawned from AI-generated music.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The same software used to clone voices has been used on famous musicians' voices to create songs that mimic their voices, gaining both tremendous popularity and criticism.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similar techniques have also been used to create improved quality or full-length versions of songs that have been leaked or have yet to be released.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been noted for its use by state-sponsored propaganda campaigns in information laundering.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a 2025 report by Graphika, generative AI is used to launder articles from Chinese state media such as China Global Television Network through various social media sites in an attempt to disguise the articles' origin.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A paper published by researchers at Amazon Web Services AI Labs found that over 57% of sentences from a sample of over 6 billion sentences from Common Crawl, a snapshot of web pages, were machine translated.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many of these automated translations were seen as lower quality, especially for sentences that were translated into at least three languages.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Wolof, Xhosa) were translated across more languages than higher-resource languages (ex.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI tools led to an explosion of AI-generated content across multiple domains.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study from University College London estimated that in 2023, more than 60,000 scholarly articles—over 1% of all publications—were likely written with LLM assistance.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to Stanford University's Institute for Human-Centered AI, approximately 17.5% of newly published computer science papers and 16.9% of peer review text now incorporate content generated by LLMs.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] If AI-generated content is included in new data crawls from the Internet for additional training of AI models, defects in the resulting models may occur.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training an AI model exclusively on the output of another AI model produces a lower-quality model.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Repeating this process, where each new model is trained on the previous model's output, leads to progressive degradation and eventually results in a "model collapse" after multiple iterations.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] On the other side, synthetic data can be deployed to train machine learning models while preserving user privacy.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The approach is not limited to text generation; image generation has been employed to train computer vision models.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many websites that allow explicit AI generated images or videos have been created, and this has been used to create illegal content, such as rape, child sexual abuse material, necrophilia, and zoophilia.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI's ability to create realistic fake content has been exploited in numerous types of cybercrime, including phishing scams.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfake video and audio have been used to create disinformation and fraud.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2020, former Google click fraud czar Shuman Ghosemajumder argued that once deepfake videos become perfectly realistic, they would stop appearing remarkable to viewers, potentially leading to uncritical acceptance of false information.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, large language models and other forms of text-generation AI have been used to create fake reviews of e-commerce websites to boost ratings.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Cybercriminals have created large language models focused on fraud, including WormGPT and FraudGPT.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study showed that generative AI can be vulnerable to jailbreaks, reverse psychology and prompt injection attacks, enabling attackers to obtain help with harmful requests, such as for crafting social engineering and phishing attacks.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, other researchers have demonstrated that open-source models can be fine-tuned to remove their safety restrictions at low cost.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Israel signed a $6 million contract with the US-based firm Clock Tower X that aimed to influence ChatGPT, Gemini and Grok by spreading pro-Israel information onto social media and websites.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This was in an attempt to take advantage of the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technique which is used by LLMs to provide more up-to-date information.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from covered service providers, including some AI service providers, regardless of where the data is physically stored.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Courts can require parent companies to provide data held by their subsidiaries, and such orders may be accompanied by nondisclosure requirements preventing the provider from notifying affected users.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] This framework has been described in legal commentary as creating legal tension with Article 48 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] As a result, service providers operating in both jurisdictions may face competing legal obligations under U.S. and EU law.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI has a significant carbon footprint due to growing energy consumption from both training and usage.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is also concern that these impacts may increase as these models are incorporated into widely used search engines such as Google Search and Bing, as chatbots and other applications become more popular, and as models need to be retrained.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training frontier AI models requires an enormous amount of computing power.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Usually only Big Tech companies have the financial resources to make such investments.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller start-ups such as Cohere and OpenAI end up buying access to data centers from Google and Microsoft respectively.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Tools such as GPTZero can detect content generated by AI.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, they can also make false accusations (false positives).
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] Digital watermarking is a technique that improves detection accuracy.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] It works by altering the generated content at the source, in subtle ways which can be detected by corresponding software.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, OpenAI developed a watermarking tool for ChatGPT.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] They didn't release it, because they worried that users would switch to competitors.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] They also argued that it would be easy to circumvent, for example by asking another AI to rephrase.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2025, the Cyberspace Administration of China issued rules, requiring online service providers to label AI content.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Google deployed its watermarking tool, SynthID.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] It marks output from Gemini (text), Imagen (images), and Veo (video).
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] To detect output from these products, one uses Google's "SynthID detector" portal.
[src:dalle-model/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2025, users mistakenly accused gaming companies of using generative AI for the video games *Little Droid* and *Catly*.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI was founded in 2015 in Delaware as a nonprofit.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] A for-profit subsidiary of the nonprofit was created in 2019, and a 2025 restructuring converted the subsidiary into a PBC that is 26% owned by the nonprofit.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Microsoft previously invested over $13 billion into OpenAI, and provides Azure cloud computing resources.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI conducted a $6.6 billion share sale that valued the company at $500 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2023 and 2024, OpenAI faced multiple lawsuits for alleged copyright infringement against authors and media companies whose work was used to train some of OpenAI's products.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In November 2023, OpenAI's board removed Sam Altman as CEO, citing a lack of confidence in him, but reinstated him five days later following a reconstruction of the board.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Throughout 2024, roughly half of then-employed AI safety researchers left OpenAI, citing the company's deprioritization of safety goals.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2015, OpenAI was founded as the nonprofit organization OpenAI, Inc., by Elon Musk, Sam Altman, Ilya Sutskever, Greg Brockman, Trevor Blackwell, Vicki Cheung, Andrej Karpathy, Durk Kingma, John Schulman, Pamela Vagata, and Wojciech Zaremba, with Elon Musk and Sam Altman as the co-chairs.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] A total of $1 billion in capital was pledged by Elon Musk, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman, Reid Hoffman, Jessica Livingston, Peter Thiel, Amazon Web Services (AWS), and Infosys.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] However, the actual capital collected significantly lagged pledges.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] According to tax filings, only $133.2 million had been received by 2021.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Elon Musk stated in 2015 that he was partly motivated by concerns about AI safety and existential risk from artificial general intelligence.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that "it's hard to fathom how much human-level AI could benefit society", and that it is equally difficult to comprehend "how much it could damage society if built or used incorrectly".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The startup also wrote that AI "should be an extension of individual human wills and, in the spirit of liberty, as broadly and evenly distributed as possible", and that "because of AI's surprising history, it's hard to predict when human-level AI might come within reach.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] When it does, it'll be important to have a leading research institution which can prioritize a good outcome for all over its own self-interest." Co-chair Sam Altman expected a decades-long project that eventually surpasses human intelligence.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI was initially run from Brockman's living room.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It was later headquartered at the Pioneer Building in the Mission District, San Francisco.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Brockman met with Yoshua Bengio, one of the "founding fathers" of deep learning, and drew up a list of great AI researchers.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Brockman was able to hire nine of them as the first employees in December 2015.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI did not pay AI researchers salaries comparable to those of Facebook or Google.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It also did not pay stock options which AI researchers typically get.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Nevertheless, OpenAI spent $7 million on its first 52 employees in 2016.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2016, OpenAI released a public beta of "OpenAI Gym", its platform for reinforcement learning research.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Nvidia gifted its first DGX-1 supercomputer to OpenAI in August 2016 to help it train larger and more complex AI models with the capability of reducing processing time from six days to two hours.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2016, OpenAI released "Universe", a software platform for measuring and training an AI's general intelligence across the world's supply of games, websites, and other applications.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2019, OpenAI transitioned from nonprofit to "capped" for-profit, with the profit being capped at 100 times any investment.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI formed three subsidiaries: the holding company OpenAI LP, the holding company OpenAI GP LLC, and the capped for-profit company OpenAI Global, LLC.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The holding company OpenAI LP was owned by the nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., OpenAI employees, and investors, whereas OpenAI Global, LLC, was owned by OpenAI LP and Microsoft, the latter of which had a minority non-voting stake.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., controlled OpenAI GP LLC, which in turn controlled OpenAI LP and OpenAI Global, LLC.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that the capped-profit model would allow it to legally attract investment from venture funds and compensate employees with equity as competing AI companies did.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Microsoft subsequently invested $1 billion in OpenAI LP, and OpenAI's services were migrated to Microsoft Azure.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Since then, OpenAI systems have run on an Azure-based supercomputing platform.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The 2019 restructuring made the nonprofit OpenAI, Inc., the only controlling shareholder of OpenAI LP, which retained a formal fiduciary responsibility to OpenAI, Inc.'s nonprofit charter.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] A majority of OpenAI, Inc.'s board was barred from having financial stakes in OpenAI LP.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In addition, minority members with a stake in OpenAI LP were barred from certain votes due to conflict of interest.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Some researchers have argued that OpenAI's switch to for-profit status was inconsistent with OpenAI's claims to be "democratizing" AI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI proposed a restructuring plan to convert the capped-profit into a Delaware-based public benefit corporation (PBC), remove its profit cap, and release it from the control of the nonprofit.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The nonprofit would sell its control and other assets, getting equity in return, and would use it to fund and pursue separate charitable projects, including in science and education.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI's leadership described the change as necessary to secure additional investments, and claimed that the nonprofit's founding mission to ensure AGI "benefits all of humanity" would be better fulfilled.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The plan has been criticized by former employees.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] A legal letter named "Not For Private Gain" asked the attorneys general of California and Delaware to intervene, stating that the restructuring is illegal and would remove governance safeguards from the nonprofit and the attorneys general.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The letter argues that OpenAI's complex structure was deliberately designed to remain accountable to its mission, without the conflicting pressure of maximizing profits.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It contends that the nonprofit is best positioned to advance its mission of ensuring AGI benefits all of humanity by continuing to control OpenAI Global, LLC, whatever the amount of equity that it could get in exchange.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] PBCs can choose how they balance their mission with profit-making.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Controlling shareholders have a large influence on how closely a PBC sticks to its mission.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI subpoenaed six nonprofit organizations that opposed its for-profit transition, which the organizations described as an attempt to silence them.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On October 28, 2025, OpenAI announced that it had adopted the new PBC corporate structure after receiving approval from the attorneys general of California and Delaware.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Under the new structure, OpenAI's for-profit branch became a public benefit corporation known as OpenAI Group PBC, while the nonprofit was renamed to the OpenAI Foundation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The OpenAI Foundation holds a 26% stake in the PBC, while Microsoft holds a 27% stake and the remaining 47% is owned by employees and other investors.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] All members of the OpenAI Group PBC board of directors are to be appointed by the OpenAI Foundation, which can remove them at any time.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] As of April 2026, all but one of the board members of the OpenAI Foundation were also board members of OpenAI Group PBC.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, co-founder Musk revised his lawsuit against OpenAI and Altman to seek the reversal of OpenAI's corporate restructuring.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Musk lost the lawsuit in May 2026, with the jury concluding that he waited beyond the three-year statute of limitations to sue OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Also in May 2026, *Bloomberg* reported that OpenAI was preparing to confidentially file its IPO, seeking to publicly debut in the Fall of that same year.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Following its original $1 billion investment in 2019, Microsoft invested another $2 billion through 2022.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On January 23, 2023, Microsoft announced an additional US$10 billion investment in OpenAI over multiple years, of which a significant portion would be used to purchase compute on Microsoft Azure.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] These investments were made at a $29 billion valuation, double OpenAI's 2021 valuation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Later that year, Microsoft began using OpenAI models for its Copilot chatbot, integrated Copilot into Windows, and released mobile Copilot apps.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Following OpenAI's 2025 restructuring, Microsoft owned a 27% stake in the for-profit OpenAI Group PBC, valued at $135 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In a deal announced the same day, OpenAI agreed to purchase $250 billion of Azure services, with Microsoft ceding their right of first refusal over OpenAI's future cloud computing purchases.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] As part of the deal, OpenAI will continue to share 20% of its revenue with Microsoft until it achieves AGI, which must now be verified by an independent panel of experts.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The deal also loosened restrictions on both companies working with third parties, allowing Microsoft to pursue AGI independently and allowing OpenAI to develop products with other companies.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, the two firms announced a new agreement which removed many of the more restrictive aspects of their partnership.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] No longer the exclusive cloud provider, Microsoft then had the first right to provide cloud services, but OpenAI could purchase other services in the event that Microsoft did not provide sufficient capacity.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI will no longer receive a portion of Microsoft's revenue from using OpenAI's technology.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The artificial general intelligence clause which created uncertainty for Microsoft in the event OpenAI determined that they had created AGI was dropped.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2017, OpenAI spent $7.9 million, a quarter of its functional expenses, on cloud computing alone.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In comparison, DeepMind's total expenses in 2017 were $442 million.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In the summer of 2018, training OpenAI's *Dota 2* bots required renting 128,000 CPUs and 256 GPUs from Google for multiple weeks.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Microsoft's 2019 investment in OpenAI, totaling $1 billion, reportedly kicked off the "contemporary AI boom".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2024, OpenAI completed a $6.6 billion capital raise with a $157 billion valuation including investments from Microsoft, Nvidia, and SoftBank.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On January 21, 2025, Donald Trump announced The Stargate Project, a joint venture between OpenAI, Oracle, SoftBank and MGX to build an AI infrastructure system in conjunction with the US government.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The project takes its name from OpenAI's existing "Stargate" supercomputer project and is estimated to cost $500 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The partners planned to fund the project over the next four years.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In July, the United States Department of Defense announced that OpenAI had received a $200 million contract for AI in the military, along with Anthropic, Google, and xAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In the same month, the company made a deal with the UK Government to use ChatGPT and other AI tools in public services.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI subsequently began a $50 million fund to support nonprofit and community organizations.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2025, OpenAI raised $40 billion at a $300 billion post-money valuation, which was the highest-value private technology deal in history.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The financing round was led by SoftBank, with other participants including Microsoft, Coatue, Altimeter and Thrive.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In July 2025, the company reported annualized revenue of $12 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] This was an increase from $3.7 billion in 2024, which was driven by ChatGPT subscriptions, which reached 20 million paid subscribers by April 2025, up from 15.5 million at the end of 2024, alongside a rapidly expanding enterprise customer base that grew to five million business users.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In February 2026, OpenAI raised $110 billion at a $730 billion valuation, led by Amazon ($50 billion), SoftBank ($30 billion), and Nvidia ($30 billion), surpassing the prior round as the largest private technology fundraise in history.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The round was later extended to $120 billion in March 2026.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, the company announced that it closed a funding round of $122 billion in committed capital at a post-money valuation of $852 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The for-profit structure established in 2025 allows the PBC to raise investor funds like most traditional tech companies, including through an initial public offering (IPO), which Altman claimed was the most likely path forward.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On June 8, 2026, OpenAI confirmed it filed for an IPO with the US Securities and Exchange.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI uses a tiered revenue model that combines free consumer access, paid subscription services, enterprise licensing, and application programming interface (API) usage-based pricing.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The basic functionality is provided at no cost, while advanced capabilities are offered through paid plans such as ChatGPT Plus and enterprise solutions.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI's subscription and enterprise offerings are structured around scalable compute usage and API integration into third-party platforms.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2025, the company reported significant revenue growth associated with expanded computing infrastructure and enterprise adoption.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The company's cash burn remains high because of the intensive computational costs required to train and operate large language models.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It projects an $8 billion operating loss in 2025.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI reports revised long-term spending projections totaling approximately $115 billion through 2029, with annual expenditures projected to escalate significantly, reaching $17 billion in 2026, $35 billion in 2027, and $45 billion in 2028.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The company's financial strategy prioritizes market expansion and technological advancement over near-term profitability, with OpenAI's 2025 forecast predicting cash-flow-positive operations by 2029 and projecting revenue of approximately $200 billion by 2030.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI completed an employee share sale of up to $10 billion to existing investors which valued the company at $500 billion.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The deal valued OpenAI as the most valuable privately owned company in the world—surpassing SpaceX as the world's most valuable private company.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, reports indicated that OpenAI projected approximately $2.5 billion in advertising revenue for the year, with estimates rising to $100 billion annually by 2030, highlighting advertising as a key component of its future business strategy.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2026, it was announced that OpenAI and the White House have been in ongoing talks for about a year to allow a possible government stake in the company.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In August 2023, it was announced that OpenAI had acquired the New York-based start-up Global Illumination, a company that deploys AI to develop digital infrastructure and creative tools.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2024, OpenAI acquired Multi, a startup focused on remote collaboration.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On February 10, 2025, a consortium of investors led by Elon Musk submitted a $97.4 billion unsolicited bid to buy the nonprofit that controls OpenAI, declaring willingness to match or exceed any better offer.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The offer was rejected on 14 February 2025, with OpenAI stating that it was not for sale, but the offer complicated Altman's restructuring plan by suggesting a lower bar for how much the nonprofit should be valued.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In March 2025, OpenAI reached a deal with CoreWeave to acquire $350 million worth of CoreWeave shares and access to AI infrastructure, in return for $11.9 billion paid over five years.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Microsoft was already CoreWeave's biggest customer in 2024.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Alongside their other business dealings, OpenAI and Microsoft were renegotiating the terms of their partnership to facilitate a potential future IPO by OpenAI, while ensuring Microsoft's continued access to advanced AI models.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On May 21, 2025 OpenAI announced the $6.5 billion acquisition of io, an AI hardware start-up founded by former Apple designer Jony Ive in 2024.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI agreed to acquire the product testing startup Statsig for $1.1 billion in an all-stock deal and appointed Statsig's founding CEO Vijaye Raji as OpenAI's chief technology officer of applications.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The company also announced development of an AI-driven hiring service designed to rival LinkedIn.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI acquired personal finance app Roi in October 2025.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI acquired Software Applications Incorporated, the developer of Sky, a macOS-based natural language interface designed to operate across desktop applications.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The Sky team joined OpenAI, and the company announced plans to integrate Sky's capabilities into ChatGPT.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2025, it was announced OpenAI had agreed to acquire Neptune, an AI tooling startup that helps companies track and manage model training, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In January 2026, it was announced OpenAI had acquired healthcare technology startup Torch for approximately $60 million.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The acquisition followed the launch of OpenAI's ChatGPT Health product and was intended to strengthen the company's medical data and healthcare artificial intelligence capabilities.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI acquired Python tool developer Astral in March 2026.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, the company acquired TBPN, a media company in California, for an undisclosed sum.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI has been criticized for outsourcing the annotation of data sets to Sama, a company based in San Francisco that employed workers in Kenya.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] These annotations were used to train an AI model to detect toxicity, which could then be used to moderate toxic content, notably from ChatGPT's training data and outputs.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] However, these pieces of text usually contained detailed descriptions of various types of violence, including sexual violence.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI began sending snippets of data to Sama as early as November 2021.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The four Sama employees interviewed by *Time* described themselves as mentally scarred.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI paid Sama $12.50 per hour of work, and Sama was redistributing the equivalent of between $1.32 and $2.00 per hour post-tax to its annotators.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Sama's spokesperson said that the $12.50 was also covering other implicit costs, among which were infrastructure expenses, quality assurance and management.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2024, OpenAI began collaborating with Broadcom to design a custom AI chip capable of both training and inference, targeted for mass production in 2026 and to be manufactured by TSMC on a 3 nm process node.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] This initiative intended to reduce OpenAI's dependence on Nvidia GPUs, which are costly and face high demand in the market.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In January 2024, Arizona State University purchased ChatGPT Enterprise in OpenAI's first deal with a university.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2024, Apple Inc. signed a contract with OpenAI to integrate ChatGPT features into its products as part of its new Apple Intelligence initiative.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI partnered with Anduril Industries to develop and deploy advanced artificial intelligence solutions for national security missions.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2025, OpenAI began renting Google Cloud's Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) to support ChatGPT and related services, marking its first meaningful use of non‑Nvidia AI chips.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In September 2025, it was revealed that OpenAI signed a contract with Oracle to purchase $300 billion in computing power over the next five years.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI and NVIDIA announced a memorandum of understanding that included a potential deployment of at least 10 gigawatts of NVIDIA systems and a $100 billion investment from NVIDIA in OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI expected the negotiations to be completed within weeks.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] As of January 2026, this has not been realized, and the two sides are rethinking the future of their partnership.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2025, OpenAI announced a multi-billion dollar deal with AMD.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI committed to purchasing six gigawatts worth of AMD chips, starting with the MI450.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI will have the option to buy up to 160 million shares of AMD, about 10% of the company, depending on development, performance and share price targets.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2025, Disney said it would make a $1 billion investment in OpenAI, and signed a three-year licensing deal that will let users generate videos using Sora—OpenAI's short-form AI video platform.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] More than 200 Disney, Marvel, Star Wars and Pixar characters would be available to OpenAI users.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Disney would later exit this deal in late March 2026, due to Sora being discontinued.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In early 2026, Amazon entered advanced discussions to invest up to $50 billion in OpenAI as part of a potential artificial intelligence partnership.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Under the proposed agreement, OpenAI's models could be integrated into Amazon's digital assistant Alexa and other internal projects.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2026, OpenAI announced partnerships with Wix, Base44, Replit, Lovable, Figma, and Emergent to support its new Sites feature in Codex, which enables users to publish outputs as hosted, interactive websites rather than local files.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On June 24, 2026, OpenAI announced its new chip called Jalapeño, created in collaboration with Broadcom.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The company plans to start rolling it out by the end of 2026.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI provides LLMs to the Artificial Intelligence Cyber Challenge and to the Advanced Research Projects Agency for Health.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In October 2024, The Intercept revealed that OpenAI's tools are considered "essential" for AFRICOM's mission and included in an "Exception to Fair Opportunity" contractual agreement between the United States Department of Defense (DoD) and Microsoft.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2024, OpenAI said it would partner with defense-tech company Anduril to build drone defense technologies for the United States and its allies.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2025, OpenAI's Chief Product Officer, Kevin Weil, was commissioned lieutenant colonel in the U.S.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Army to join Detachment 201 as senior advisor.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In June 2025, the DoD awarded OpenAI a $200 million one-year contract to develop AI tools for military and national security applications.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI announced a new program, OpenAI for Government, to give federal, state, and local governments access to its models, including ChatGPT.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On 28 February 2026, after OpenAI's competitor Anthropic refused to authorize the DoD to use its AI systems for mass surveillance or autonomous weapons systems, it was labeled a "supply-chain risk" by the DoD and the Trump administration decided to stop using it across the government.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The same day, OpenAI announced that it had reached an agreement with the DoD to deploy its models in the government's classified network.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] CEO Sam Altman wrote, "Two of our most important safety principles are prohibitions on domestic mass surveillance and human responsibility for the use of force, including for autonomous weapon systems", that the DoD agrees with this, and that this is included in their agreement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] However, while the agreement mentioned existing law and allowed OpenAI to implement some technical safeguards, it did not incorporate legally binding prohibitions on domestic mass surveillance or fully autonomous weapons.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Following backlash over the potential use of ChatGPT for surveillance, Altman amended the contract to include more safeguards, though only excerpts of the contract were made public and critics remained concerned that it was purposefully vague and contained carve-outs for domestic surveillance.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In February 2019, GPT-2 was announced, which gained attention for its ability to generate human-like text.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2020, OpenAI announced GPT-3, a language model trained on large internet datasets.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] GPT-3 is aimed at natural language answering questions, but it can also translate between languages and coherently generate improvised text.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It also announced that an associated API, named *the API*, would form the heart of its first commercial product.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Eleven employees left OpenAI, mostly between December 2020 and January 2021, in order to establish Anthropic.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2021, OpenAI introduced DALL-E, a specialized deep learning model adept at generating complex digital images from textual descriptions, utilizing a variant of the GPT-3 architecture.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2022, OpenAI received widespread media coverage after launching a free preview of ChatGPT, its new AI chatbot based on GPT-3.5.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] According to OpenAI, the preview received over a million signups within the first five days.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] According to anonymous sources cited by Reuters in December 2022, OpenAI Global, LLC was projecting $200 million of revenue in 2023 and $1 billion in revenue in 2024.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] After ChatGPT was launched, Google announced a similar chatbot, Bard, amid internal concerns that ChatGPT could threaten Google's position as a primary source of online information.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On February 7, 2023, Microsoft announced that it was building AI technology based on the same foundation as ChatGPT into Microsoft Bing, Edge, Microsoft 365 and other products.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On March 14, 2023, OpenAI released GPT-4, both as an API (with a waitlist) and as a feature of ChatGPT Plus.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 6, 2023, OpenAI launched GPTs, allowing individuals to create customized versions of ChatGPT for specific purposes, further expanding the possibilities of AI applications across various industries.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 14, 2023, OpenAI announced they temporarily suspended new sign-ups for ChatGPT Plus due to high demand.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Access for newer subscribers re-opened a month later on December 13.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In December 2024, the company launched the Sora model.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It also launched OpenAI o1, an early reasoning model that was internally codenamed *strawberry*.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Additionally, ChatGPT Pro—a $200/month subscription service offering unlimited o1 access and enhanced voice features—was introduced, and preliminary benchmark results for the upcoming OpenAI o3 models were shared.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On January 23, 2025, OpenAI released Operator, an AI agent and tool for accessing websites to execute goals defined by users.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The feature was only available to Pro users in the United States.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI released deep research agent, nine days later.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] It scored a 27% accuracy on the benchmark Humanity's Last Exam (HLE).
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Altman later stated GPT-4.5 would be the last model without full chain-of-thought reasoning.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In July 2025, according to OpenAI, one of its experimental models performed at a gold medal-level at the International Mathematical Olympiad.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On October 6, 2025, OpenAI displayed its Agent Builder platform during the company's DevDay event.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The platform includes a visual drag-and-drop interface for agentic workflows.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On October 21, 2025, OpenAI introduced ChatGPT Atlas, a web browser which integrates ChatGPT into web navigation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On December 11, 2025, OpenAI announced GPT-5.2.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In early 2026, reports indicated that OpenAI was working on a collaborative software development platform designed to compete with services such as GitHub and GitLab.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In March 2023, the company was criticized for disclosing particularly few technical details about products like GPT-4, contradicting its initial commitment to openness and making it harder for independent researchers to replicate its work and develop safeguards.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI cited competitiveness and safety concerns to justify this repudiation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI's former chief scientist Ilya Sutskever argued in 2023 that open-sourcing increasingly capable models was increasingly risky, and that the safety reasons for not open-sourcing the most potent AI models would become "obvious" in a few years.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In September 2025, OpenAI published a study on how people use ChatGPT for everyday tasks.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The study found that "non-work tasks" (according to an LLM-based classifier) account for more than 72 percent of all ChatGPT usage, with a minority of overall usage related to business productivity.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In July 2023, OpenAI launched the superalignment project, aiming within four years to determine how to align future superintelligent systems.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI promised to dedicate 20% of its computing resources to the project, although the company's employees later reported that the company only allocated 1–2% of its resources to it.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI ended the project in May 2024 after its co-leaders Ilya Sutskever and Jan Leike left the company.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In August 2025, OpenAI was criticized after thousands of private ChatGPT conversations were inadvertently exposed to public search engines like Google due to an experimental "share with search engines" feature.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The opt-in toggle, intended to allow users to make specific chats discoverable, resulted in some discussions including personal details such as names, locations, and intimate topics appearing in search results when users accidentally enabled it while sharing links.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI announced the feature's permanent removal on August 1, 2025, and the company began coordinating with search providers to remove the exposed content, emphasizing that it was not a security breach but a design flaw that heightened privacy risks.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] CEO Sam Altman acknowledged the issue in a podcast, noting users often treat ChatGPT as a confidant for deeply personal matters, which amplified concerns about AI handling sensitive data.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 17, 2023, Sam Altman was removed as CEO when OpenAI's board of directors (composed of Helen Toner, Ilya Sutskever, Adam D'Angelo and Tasha McCauley) cited a lack of confidence in him.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Chief Technology Officer Mira Murati took over as interim CEO.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Greg Brockman, the president of OpenAI, was also removed as chairman of the board and resigned from the company's presidency shortly thereafter.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Three senior OpenAI researchers subsequently resigned: director of research and GPT-4 lead Jakub Pachocki, head of AI risk Aleksander Mądry, and researcher Szymon Sidor.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 18, 2023, there were reportedly talks of Altman returning as CEO amid pressure placed upon the board by investors such as Microsoft and Thrive Capital, who objected to Altman's departure.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Although Altman himself spoke in favor of returning to OpenAI, he has since stated that he considered starting a new company and bringing former OpenAI employees with him if talks to reinstate him did not work out.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Altman insisted multiple times that all board members who supported his removal should resign; the board members agreed "in principle" to resign if Altman returned.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 19, 2023, negotiations with Altman to return failed and Murati was replaced by Emmett Shear as interim CEO.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] The board initially contacted Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei (a former OpenAI executive) about replacing Altman, and proposed a merger of the two companies, but both offers were declined.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 20, 2023, Microsoft CEO Satya Nadella announced Altman and Brockman would be joining Microsoft to lead a new advanced AI research team, but added that they were still committed to OpenAI despite recent events.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Before the partnership with Microsoft was finalized, Altman gave the board another opportunity to negotiate with him.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] About 738 of OpenAI's 770 employees, including Murati and Sutskever, signed an open letter stating they would quit their jobs and join Microsoft if the board did not rehire Altman and then resign.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] This prompted OpenAI investors to consider legal action against the board as well.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In response, OpenAI management sent an internal memo to employees stating that negotiations with Altman and the board had resumed and would take some time.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 21, 2023, after continued negotiations, Altman and Brockman returned to the company in their prior roles along with a reconstructed board made up of new members Bret Taylor (as chairman) and Lawrence Summers, with D'Angelo remaining.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] According to subsequent reporting, shortly before Altman's firing, some employees raised concerns to the board about how he had handled the safety implications of a recent internal AI capability discovery.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On November 29, 2023, OpenAI announced that an anonymous Microsoft employee had joined the board as a non-voting member to observe the company's operations; Microsoft resigned from the board in July 2024.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In February 2024, the Securities and Exchange Commission subpoenaed OpenAI's internal communication to determine if Altman's alleged lack of candor misled investors.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Following the temporary removal of Sam Altman and his return, many employees gradually left OpenAI, including most of the original leadership team and a significant number of AI safety researchers.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In 2018, Musk resigned from his Board of Directors seat, citing "a potential future conflict [of interest]" with his role as CEO of Tesla due to Tesla's AI development for self-driving cars.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI stated that Musk's financial contributions were below $45 million.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] On March 3, 2023, Reid Hoffman resigned from his board seat, citing a desire to avoid conflicts of interest with his investments in AI companies via Greylock Partners, and his co-founding of the AI startup Inflection AI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Hoffman remained on the board of Microsoft, a major investor in OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In May 2024, Chief Scientist Ilya Sutskever resigned and was succeeded by Jakub Pachocki.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Co-leader Jan Leike also departed amid concerns over safety and trust.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] OpenAI then signed deals with Reddit, News Corp, Axios, and Vox Media.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Paul Nakasone then joined the board of OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In August 2024, cofounder John Schulman left OpenAI to join Anthropic, and OpenAI's president Greg Brockman took extended leave until November.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In September 2024, CTO Mira Murati left the company.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In November 2025, Lawrence Summers resigned from the board of directors.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] In April 2026, OpenAI's head of AGI deployment, Fidji Simo, said she would take "several weeks" of medical leave.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] This triggered a reshuffling of the leadership.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Brad Lightcap transitioned from his role as Chief Operating Officer to lead "special projects" focused on complex deals, reporting directly to Sam Altman.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] This includes a potential software distribution joint venture with private equity partners.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p01] Denise Dresser, the company's Chief Revenue Officer, temporarily assumed several of Lightcap's previous operational duties, with Greg Brockman taking over the product organization.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In May 2023, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman and Ilya Sutskever posted recommendations for the governance of superintelligence.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] They stated that superintelligence could happen within the next 10 years, allowing a "dramatically more prosperous future" and that "given the possibility of existential risk, we can't just be reactive".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] They proposed creating an international watchdog organization similar to IAEA to oversee AI systems above a certain capability threshold, suggesting that relatively weak AI systems, on the other hand, should not be overly regulated.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] They also called for more technical safety research for superintelligences, and asked for more coordination, for example through governments launching a joint project which "many current efforts become part of".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In July 2023, the FTC issued a civil investigative demand to OpenAI to investigate whether the company's data security and privacy practices to develop ChatGPT were unfair or harmed consumers (including by reputational harm) in violation of Section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission Act of 1914.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] These are typically preliminary investigative matters and are nonpublic, but the FTC's document was leaked.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] They asked OpenAI for comprehensive information about its technology and privacy safeguards, as well as any steps taken to prevent the recurrence of situations in which its chatbot generated false and disparaging content about people.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The agency also raised concerns about 'circular' spending arrangements—for example, Microsoft extending Azure credits to OpenAI while both companies shared engineering talent—and warned that such structures could negatively affect the public.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In September 2024, OpenAI's global affairs chief endorsed the UK's "smart" AI regulation during testimony to a House of Lords committee.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In February 2025, OpenAI CEO Sam Altman stated that the company is interested in collaborating with the People's Republic of China, despite regulatory restrictions imposed by the U.S. government.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] This shift comes in response to the growing influence of the Chinese artificial intelligence company DeepSeek, which has disrupted the AI market with open models, including DeepSeek V3 and DeepSeek R1.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Following DeepSeek's market emergence, OpenAI enhanced security protocols to protect proprietary development techniques from industrial espionage.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Some industry observers noted similarities between DeepSeek's model distillation approach and OpenAI's methodology, though no formal intellectual property claim was filed.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] According to Oliver Roberts, in March 2025, the United States had 781 state AI bills or laws.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI advocated for preempting state AI laws with federal laws.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] According to Scott Kohler, OpenAI has opposed California's AI legislation and suggested that the state bill encroaches on a more competent federal government.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Public Citizen opposed a federal preemption on AI and pointed to OpenAI's growth and valuation as evidence that existing state laws have not hampered innovation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In early 2026, OpenAI provided the entire initial funding for the Parents & Kids Safe AI Coalition.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Several organizations contacted on behalf of the coalition reported being unaware of OpenAI's involvement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Before May 2024, OpenAI required departing employees to sign a lifelong non-disparagement agreement forbidding them from criticizing OpenAI or acknowledging the existence of the agreement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Daniel Kokotajlo, a former employee, publicly stated that he forfeited his vested equity in OpenAI in order to leave without signing the agreement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Sam Altman stated that he was unaware of the equity cancellation provision, and that OpenAI never enforced it to cancel any employee's vested equity.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] However, leaked documents and emails refute this claim.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On May 23, 2024, OpenAI sent a memo releasing former employees from the agreement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI was sued for copyright infringement by authors Sarah Silverman, Matthew Butterick, Paul Tremblay and Mona Awad in July 2023.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In September 2023, 17 authors, including George R.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Martin, John Grisham, Jodi Picoult and Jonathan Franzen, joined the Authors Guild in filing a class action lawsuit against OpenAI, alleging that the company's technology was illegally using their copyrighted work.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The *New York Times* also sued the company in late December 2023.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In May 2024 it was revealed that OpenAI had destroyed its Books1 and Books2 training datasets, which were used in the training of GPT-3, and which the Authors Guild believed to have contained over 100,000 copyrighted books.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In 2021, OpenAI developed a speech recognition tool called Whisper.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI used it to transcribe more than one million hours of YouTube videos into text for training GPT-4.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The automated transcription of YouTube videos raised concerns within OpenAI employees regarding potential violations of YouTube's terms of service, which prohibit the use of videos for applications independent of the platform, as well as any type of automated access to its videos.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Despite these concerns, the project proceeded with notable involvement from OpenAI's president, Greg Brockman.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The resulting dataset proved instrumental in training GPT-4.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In February 2024, *The Intercept* as well as *Raw Story* and Alternate Media Inc. filed lawsuit against OpenAI on copyright litigation ground.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The lawsuit is said to have charted a new legal strategy for digital-only publishers to sue OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On April 30, 2024, eight newspapers filed a lawsuit in the Southern District of New York against OpenAI and Microsoft, claiming illegal harvesting of their copyrighted articles.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The suing publications included *The Mercury News*, *The Denver Post*, *The Orange County Register*, *St.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Paul Pioneer Press*, *Chicago Tribune*, *Orlando Sentinel*, *Sun Sentinel*, and *New York Daily News*.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In June 2023, a lawsuit claimed that OpenAI scraped 300 billion words online without consent and without registering as a data broker.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] It was filed in San Francisco, California, by sixteen anonymous plaintiffs.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] They also claimed that OpenAI and its partner as well as customer Microsoft continued to unlawfully collect and use personal data from millions of consumers worldwide to train artificial intelligence models.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On May 22, 2024, OpenAI entered into an agreement with News Corp to integrate news content from *The Wall Street Journal*, the *New York Post*, *The Times*, and *The Sunday Times* into its AI platform.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Meanwhile, other publications like *The New York Times* chose to sue OpenAI and Microsoft for copyright infringement over the use of their content to train AI models.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In November 2024, a coalition of Canadian news outlets, including the Toronto Star, Metroland Media, Postmedia, The Globe and Mail, The Canadian Press and CBC, sued OpenAI for using their news articles to train its software without permission.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In October 2024 during a New York Times interview, Suchir Balaji accused OpenAI of violating copyright law in developing its commercial LLMs which he had helped engineer.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] He was a likely witness in a major copyright trial against the AI company, and was one of several of its current or former employees named in court filings as potentially having documents relevant to the case.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On November 26, 2024, Balaji died by suicide.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] His death prompted the circulation of conspiracy theories alleging that he had been deliberately silenced.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] California Congressman Ro Khanna endorsed calls for an investigation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On April 24, 2025, Ziff Davis sued OpenAI in Delaware federal court for copyright infringement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Ziff Davis is known for publications such as ZDNet, PCMag, CNET, IGN and Lifehacker.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On June 24, 2026, a group of local newspaper publishers also sued OpenAI and Microsoft for copyright infringement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In late April 2024 NOYB filed a complaint with the Austrian Datenschutzbehörde against OpenAI for violating the European General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] A text created with ChatGPT gave a false date of birth for a living person without giving the individual the option to see the personal data used in the process.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] A request to correct the mistake was denied.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Additionally, neither the recipients of ChatGPT's work nor the sources used, could be made available, OpenAI claimed.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In Europe, OpenAI operates as OpenAI Ireland Ltd for residents in the EEA or Switzerland and OpenAI OpCo, LLC, a Delaware company for residents in the UK like in the US.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI has been criticized for allowing ChatGPT to be used for "military and warfare" since January 10, 2024, when its "usage policies" removed the ban on "activity that has high risk of physical harm, including", specifically, "weapons development" and "military and warfare".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Its new policies prohibit "[using] our service to harm yourself or others" and to "develop or use weapons".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On February 29, 2024, Elon Musk filed a lawsuit against OpenAI and CEO Sam Altman, accusing them of shifting focus from public benefit to profit maximization—a case OpenAI dismissed as "incoherent" and "frivolous", though Musk later revived legal action against Altman and others in August.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On April 9, 2024, OpenAI countersued Musk in federal court, alleging that he had engaged in "bad-faith tactics" to slow the company's progress and seize its innovations for his personal benefit.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI also argued that Musk had previously supported the creation of a for-profit structure and had expressed interest in controlling OpenAI himself.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The countersuit seeks damages and legal measures to prevent further alleged interference.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Musk amended his filing on April 7, 2026, to demand that OpenAI undo its transition from a non-profit to a for-profit corporate structure.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The jury for the case against OpenAI, Altman and Greg Brockman was seated on April 27, 2026.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On April 28, 2026, trial testimony was underway, with Elon Musk beginning his testimony against Altman and OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On April 30, 2026 Musk would enter his third day of testimony.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On May 18, 2026, following a federal jury verdict in favor of OpenAI, Sam Altman, Greg Brockman and Microsoft in Musk v.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In August 2025, the parents of a 16-year-old boy who died by suicide filed a wrongful death lawsuit, *Raine v.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI*, against the company (and CEO Sam Altman), alleging that months of conversations with ChatGPT about mental health and methods of self-harm contributed to their son's death and that safeguards were inadequate for minors.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI expressed condolences and said it was strengthening protections (including updated crisis response behavior and parental controls).
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Coverage described it as a first-of-its-kind wrongful death case targeting the company's chatbot.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The complaint was filed in California state court in San Francisco.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In November 2025, the Social Media Victims Law Center and Tech Justice Law Project filed seven lawsuits against OpenAI, of which four lawsuits alleged wrongful death.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The suits were filed on behalf of Zane Shamblin, 23, of Texas; Amaurie Lacey, 17, of Georgia; Joshua Enneking, 26, of Florida; and Joe Ceccanti, 48, of Oregon, who each committed suicide after prolonged ChatGPT usage.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In December 2025, after Suzanne Adams was murdered by her 56-year-old son, First County Bank, the executor of Adams's estate, filed a lawsuit against OpenAI.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The lawsuit alleges that over months of conversations, ChatGPT validated her son's many paranoid beliefs, such as that his mother was spying on him and that she attempted to poison him using drugs siphoned through his car air vents.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI said they would make ChatGPT safer for users disconnected from reality.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] After 8 victims were killed on February 10, 2026, in mass shootings in Tumbler Ridge, British Columbia, it emerged that OpenAI had banned an account belonging to the perpetrator due to violent queries approximately 7 months prior to the attacks.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] OpenAI opted not to report the account to authorities at the time.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The *Wall Street Journal* reported that the perpetrator "described scenarios [to ChatGPT] involving gun violence over the course of several days", and that these messages were "flagged by an automated review system" and "alarmed employees at OpenAI".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] A dozen employees debated whether to take action, some urging leaders to alert Canadian law enforcement.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Canadian officials summoned OpenAI's safety team to Ottawa, criticizing their escalation protocols.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The meeting highlighted concerns about how and when OpenAI reports potentially dangerous user behavior to authorities and intensified scrutiny of its safety-oversight processes.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] On February 23, BC Premier David Eby said, "From the outside, it looks like OpenAI had the opportunity to prevent this tragedy, to prevent this horrific loss of life, to prevent there from being dead children in British Columbia".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] Canada's federal AI Minister Evan Solomon said, "I want [OpenAI] to give us details of what their protocols are, [and] what they are specifically in Canada".
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] In 2026, a woman filed a lawsuit against OpenAI, alleging that ChatGPT played a role in enabling a prolonged stalking campaign against her.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] According to the complaint, her former partner became increasingly fixated and used the chatbot to generate messages and content that reinforced his behavior, including harassing and defamatory material.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The plaintiff claimed that she had contacted OpenAI to report the issue, but that the company did not take adequate action to prevent further misuse.
[src:dalle-model/openai-p02] The case has been cited as part of growing legal and public debate over the responsibility of AI companies to address harmful or abusive uses of their systems.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A **text-to-image** (**T2I** or **TTI**) **model** is a machine learning model which takes an input natural language prompt and produces an image matching that description.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Text-to-image models gradually began to be developed in the mid-2010s during the beginnings of the AI boom, as a result of advances in deep neural networks.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] In 2022, the output of state-of-the-art text-to-image models—such as OpenAI's DALL-E 2, Google Brain's Imagen, Stability AI's Stable Diffusion, Midjourney, and Runway's Gen-4—began to be considered to approach the quality of real photographs and human-drawn art.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Text-to-image models are generally latent diffusion models, which perform the diffusion process in a compressed latent space rather than directly in pixel space.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] An autoencoder (often a variational autoencoder (VAE)) is used to convert between pixel space and this latent representation.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] These systems typically use a pretrained language or vision–language model to convert the input prompt into a text embedding, and a diffusion-based generative image model that produces images conditioned on that embedding.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The most effective models have generally been trained on massive amounts of image and text data scraped from the web.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Before the rise of deep learning in the 2010s, attempts to build text-to-image models were limited to collages by arranging existing component images, such as from a database of clip art.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The inverse task, image captioning, was more tractable, and a number of image captioning deep learning models came prior to the first text-to-image models.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The first modern text-to-image model, alignDRAW, was introduced in 2015 by researchers from the University of Toronto. alignDRAW extended the previously-introduced DRAW architecture (which used a recurrent variational autoencoder with an attention mechanism) to be conditioned on text sequences.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Images generated by alignDRAW were in small resolution (32×32 pixels, attained from resizing) and were considered to be 'low in diversity'.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The model was able to generalize to objects not represented in the training data (such as a red school bus) and appropriately handled novel prompts such as "a stop sign is flying in blue skies", exhibiting output that it was not merely "memorizing" data from the training set.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] In 2016, Reed, Akata, Yan et al. became the first to use generative adversarial networks for the text-to-image task.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] With models trained on narrow, domain-specific datasets, they were able to generate "visually plausible" images of birds and flowers from text captions like *"an all black bird with a distinct thick, rounded bill"*.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A model trained on the more diverse COCO (Common Objects in Context) dataset produced images which were "from a distance... encouraging", but which lacked coherence in their details.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Later systems include VQGAN-CLIP, XMC-GAN, and GauGAN2.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] One of the first text-to-image models to capture widespread public attention was OpenAI's DALL-E, a transformer system announced in January 2021.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A successor capable of generating more complex and realistic images, DALL-E 2, was unveiled in April 2022, followed by Stable Diffusion that was publicly released in August 2022.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] In August 2022, text-to-image personalization allows to teach the model a new concept using a small set of images of a new object that was not included in the training set of the text-to-image foundation model.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] This is achieved by textual inversion, namely, finding a new text term that correspond to these images.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Additional text-to-image models appeared with Adobe in March 2023 and Black Forest Labs in August 2024.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Following other text-to-image models, language model-powered text-to-video platforms such as Runway, Make-A-Video, Imagen Video, Midjourney, and Phenaki can generate video from text and/or text/image prompts.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Text-to-image models have been built using a variety of architectures.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The text encoding step may be performed with a recurrent neural network such as a long short-term memory (LSTM) network, though transformer models have since become a more popular option.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] For the image generation step, conditional generative adversarial networks (GANs) was once widely used in early days.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Since 2020, diffusion models have become the popular option.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Rather than directly training a model to output a high-resolution image conditioned on a text embedding, a popular technique is to train a model to generate low-resolution images or latent space, and use one or more auxiliary deep learning models to upscale or decode it, filling in finer details.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Text-to-image models are trained on large datasets of (text, image) pairs, often scraped from the web.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] With their 2022 Imagen model, Google Brain reported positive results from using a large language model trained separately on a text-only corpus (with its weights subsequently frozen), a departure from the theretofore standard approach.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Training a text-to-image model requires a dataset of images paired with text captions.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] One dataset commonly used for this purpose is the COCO dataset.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Released by Microsoft in 2014, COCO consists of around 123,000 images depicting a diversity of objects with five captions per image, generated by human annotators.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Originally, the main focus of COCO was on the recognition of objects and scenes in images.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Oxford-120 Flowers and CUB-200 Birds are smaller datasets of around 10,000 images each, restricted to flowers and birds, respectively.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] It is considered less difficult to train a high-quality text-to-image model with these datasets because of their narrow range of subject matter.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] One of the largest open datasets for training text-to-image models is LAION-5B, containing more than 5 billion image-text pairs.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] This dataset was created using web scraping and automatic filtering based on similarity to high-quality artwork and professional photographs.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Because of this, however, it also contains controversial content, which has led to discussions about the ethics of its use.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Some modern AI platforms not only generate images from text but also create synthetic datasets to improve model training and fine-tuning.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] These datasets help avoid copyright issues and expand the diversity of training data.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Evaluating and comparing the quality of text-to-image models is a problem involving assessing multiple desirable properties.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A desideratum specific to text-to-image models is that generated images semantically align with the text captions used to generate them.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A number of schemes have been devised for assessing these qualities, some automated and others based on human judgement.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] A common algorithmic metric for assessing image quality and diversity is the Inception Score (IS), which is based on the distribution of labels predicted by a pretrained Inceptionv3 image classification model when applied to a sample of images generated by the text-to-image model.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] The score is increased when the image classification model predicts a single label with high probability, a scheme intended to favour "distinct" generated images.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Another popular metric is the related Fréchet inception distance, which compares the distribution of generated images and real training images according to features extracted by one of the final layers of a pretrained image classification model.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Generated images are sometimes used as sketches, low-cost experiments, inspiration, or illustrations of proof-of-concept-stage ideas.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] Additional functionalities or improvements may also relate to post-generation manual editing (i.e., polishing), such as subsequent tweaking with an image editor.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] In physical domains, concerns regarding structural integrity, material constraints, and cultural "ethno-computation" often limit AI to a "complementary enhancement" role rather than a substitute for production.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] This license can be used by individuals and organizations up to $1 million in revenue, for organizations with annual revenue more than $1 million, Stability AI Enterprise License is needed.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] All outputs are retained by users regardless of revenue.
[src:dalle-model/text-to-image-generation] For the Schnell model, the Dev model is using a non-commercial license while the Pro model is proprietary (only available as API).
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] In machine learning, a **variational autoencoder** (**VAE**) is an artificial neural network architecture introduced by Diederik P.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] It is part of the families of probabilistic graphical models and variational Bayesian methods.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Thus, the encoder maps each point (such as an image) from a large complex dataset into a distribution within the latent space, rather than to a single point in that space.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The decoder has the opposite function, which is to map from the latent space to the input space, again according to a distribution (although in practice, noise is rarely added during the decoding stage).
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] By mapping a point to a distribution instead of a single point, the network can avoid overfitting the training data.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Both networks are typically trained together with the usage of the reparameterization trick, although the variance of the noise model can be learned separately.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Although this type of model was initially designed for unsupervised learning, its effectiveness has been proven for semi-supervised learning and supervised learning.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] A variational autoencoder is a generative model with a prior and noise distribution respectively.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Usually such models are trained using the expectation-maximization meta-algorithm (e.g. probabilistic PCA, (spike & slab) sparse coding).
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Such a scheme optimizes a lower bound of the data likelihood, which is usually computationally intractable, and in doing so requires the discovery of q-distributions, or variational posteriors.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] These q-distributions are normally parameterized for each individual data point in a separate optimization process.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] However, variational autoencoders use a neural network as an amortized approach to jointly optimize across data points.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] In that way, the same parameters are reused for multiple data points, which can result in massive memory savings.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The first neural network takes as input the data points themselves, and outputs parameters for the variational distribution.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] As it maps from a known input space to the low-dimensional latent space, it is called the encoder.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The decoder is the second neural network of this model.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] It is a function that maps from the latent space to the input space, e.g. as the means of the noise distribution.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] It is possible to use another neural network that maps to the variance, however this can be omitted for simplicity.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] In such a case, the variance can be optimized with gradient descent.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] To optimize this model, one needs to know two terms: the "reconstruction error", and the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D).
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Both terms are derived from the free energy expression of the probabilistic model, and therefore differ depending on the noise distribution and the assumed prior of the data, here referred to as p-distribution.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] For example, a standard VAE task such as IMAGENET is typically assumed to have a gaussianly distributed noise; however, tasks such as binarized MNIST require a Bernoulli noise.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The KL-D from the free energy expression maximizes the probability mass of the q-distribution that overlaps with the p-distribution, which unfortunately can result in mode-seeking behaviour.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The "reconstruction" term is the remainder of the free energy expression, and requires a sampling approximation to compute its expectation value.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] More recent approaches replace Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D) with various statistical distances, see "Statistical distance VAE variants" below.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] From the point of view of probabilistic modeling, one wants to maximize the likelihood of the data x by their chosen parameterized probability distribution $p_{\theta }(x)=p(x|\theta )$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] This distribution is usually chosen to be a Gaussian $N(x|\mu ,\sigma )$ which is parameterized by $\mu$ and $\sigma$ respectively, and as a member of the exponential family it is easy to work with as a noise distribution.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Simple distributions are easy enough to maximize, however distributions where a prior is assumed over the latents z results in intractable integrals.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Let us find $p_{\theta }(x)$ via marginalizing over z .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] where $p_{\theta }({x,z})$ represents the joint distribution under $p_{\theta }$ of the observable data x and its latent representation or encoding z .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] In the vanilla variational autoencoder, z is usually taken to be a finite-dimensional vector of real numbers, and $p_{\theta }({x|z})$ to be a Gaussian distribution.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Then $p_{\theta }(x)$ is a mixture of Gaussian distributions.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Unfortunately, the computation of $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ is expensive and in most cases intractable.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] with $\phi$ defined as the set of real values that parametrize q .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] This is sometimes called *amortized inference*, since by "investing" in finding a good $q_{\phi }$ , one can later infer z from x quickly without doing any integrals.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] In this way, the problem is to find a good probabilistic autoencoder, in which the conditional likelihood distribution $p_{\theta }(x|z)$ is computed by the *probabilistic decoder*, and the approximated posterior distribution $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ is computed by the *probabilistic encoder*.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Parametrize the encoder as $E_{\phi }$ , and the decoder as $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] Like many deep learning approaches that use gradient-based optimization, VAEs require a differentiable loss function to update the network weights through backpropagation.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] For variational autoencoders, the idea is to jointly optimize the generative model parameters $\theta$ to reduce the reconstruction error between the input and the output, and $\phi$ to make $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ as close as possible to $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] As reconstruction loss, mean squared error and cross entropy are often used.
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] The Kullback–Leibler divergence $D_{KL}(q_{\phi }({z|x})\parallel p_{\theta }({z|x}))$ can be used as a loss function to squeeze $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ under $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] That is, maximizing the log-likelihood of the observed data, and minimizing the divergence from the approximate posterior $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ to the exact posterior $p_{\theta }(\cdot |x)$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] That is, we model the distribution of x conditional on z to be a Gaussian distribution centered on $D_{\theta }(z)$ .
[src:dalle-model/variational-autoencoder] For a more detailed derivation and more interpretations of ELBO and its maximization, see its main page.
